=== SECURITY HEADERS ANALYSIS ===

Source: next.config.mjs headers() function (lines 483-700)
Applied to: All non-static routes via catch-all source pattern

| Header                    | Value                                                    | Status |
|---------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------|--------|
| Strict-Transport-Security | max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload             | GOOD   |
| X-Frame-Options           | SAMEORIGIN                                               | OK     |
| X-Content-Type-Options    | nosniff                                                  | GOOD   |
| X-XSS-Protection          | 1; mode=block                                            | OK (deprecated but harmless) |
| Referrer-Policy           | origin-when-cross-origin                                 | OK     |
| Permissions-Policy        | camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=()                 | GOOD   |
| Content-Security-Policy   | See below                                                | ISSUES |
| X-DNS-Prefetch-Control    | on                                                       | OK     |

CSP ANALYSIS:
- default-src 'self' — GOOD
- script-src: PRODUCTION uses 'unsafe-inline' — MEDIUM RISK (gov scans flag this)
  - No nonce/hash strategy in place
  - DEV uses 'unsafe-eval' 'unsafe-inline' — expected for dev
- style-src: 'unsafe-inline' — MEDIUM (common but flagged by strict scanners)
- img-src: Restricted to specific domains — GOOD (no wildcard *)
- frame-ancestors: 'none' — GOOD (prevents clickjacking)
- upgrade-insecure-requests — GOOD
- base-uri 'self' — GOOD
- form-action restricted to 'self' + stripe — GOOD

ISSUES:
1. 'unsafe-inline' in script-src (production) — gov scanners will flag this as HIGH
   - Fix: Implement nonce-based CSP with Next.js
2. 'unsafe-inline' in style-src — common but flagged
   - Fix: Use CSS modules or nonce-based approach
3. No report-uri or report-to directive — cannot monitor CSP violations
